On Space Exploration Day, the United States celebrates its history of space travel and reaffirms its commitment to leading the world in space exploration. The article highlights the achievements of Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin, and Michael Collins in landing the first Americans on the Moon. It also mentions the advancements made by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) and the private sector in space exploration. The current administration is focused on returning to the Moon, growing space commerce, leading a human mission to Mars, and exploring the secrets of the universe. Space Policy Directive-3 has been signed to encourage the embrace of the commercial space industry and ensure safe and thriving space travel. The article emphasizes that the exploration and development of space represent American values and aims to secure a permanent presence beyond Earth. It concludes by acknowledging the visionary spirit of those who have contributed to scientific achievements and the importance of taking small steps towards discovery.